Repo VM Build CheckS


We should not depend on a long checklist of manual commands after each stage. Each stage should have an automated build verifier that produces a clear GO / NO-GO decision.

Final package structure
Stage 2

The corrected Stage 2 package will contain:

repoinfra-mailcow-repo-rebuild-<version>/
├── run.sh
├── build-and-verify.sh
├── verify-build.sh
├── bin/
├── config/
├── README.md
└── CHANGELOG.md

Normal execution will be one command:

sudo bash ./build-and-verify.sh

That command will automatically:

Package self-check
        ↓
Pre-build validation
        ↓
Repository build
        ↓
Post-build verification
        ↓
GO / NO-GO decision

The standalone verifier will also remain available:

sudo bash ./verify-build.sh

That allows verification to be rerun later without rebuilding the repository.

Stage 3

The Stage 3 package will use the same structure:

repoinfra-mailcow-complete-offline-annex-<version>/
├── run.sh
├── build-and-verify.sh
├── verify-build.sh
├── bin/
├── config/
├── README.md
└── CHANGELOG.md

Normal execution:

sudo bash ./build-and-verify.sh

Standalone re-verification:

sudo bash ./verify-build.sh
Stage 2 verification scope

The Stage 2 verifier will automatically check:

System and service checks
Rocky Linux 9 x86_64
Required tools installed
Apache enabled and active
Apache configuration syntax valid
Firewalld permits HTTP when active
SELinux remains Enforcing
Repository SELinux labels are correct
Repository structure
/srv/repo/rpms/base
/srv/repo/rpms/mailcow
/srv/repo/rpms/base/repodata/repomd.xml
/srv/repo/rpms/mailcow/repodata/repomd.xml
Git dependency-set validation

It will verify that matching versions exist for:

git
git-core
git-core-doc
perl-Git

It will reject a repository containing, for example:

git             2.52.0
git-core        missing
git-core-doc    missing
perl-Git        missing

It will also reject mismatched package versions.

RPM integrity and signatures

It will check:

RPM file integrity
Rocky RPM signatures
Repository metadata readability
SHA-256 manifest consistency
Dependency closure

It will run repository closure checks and fail when unresolved dependencies remain.

The validation will cover the complete Mailcow host-prerequisite package set, not only Git.

Clean-client simulation

This is the most important test.

The verifier will create a temporary DNF installation root and attempt to install the required packages using only:

http://127.0.0.1/rpms/base/
http://127.0.0.1/rpms/mailcow/

All public repositories will be disabled.

Conceptually, it will perform:

dnf \
  --installroot <temporary-root> \
  --disablerepo='*' \
  --enablerepo=linuxinfra-base,linuxinfra-mailcow \
  install <required-packages>

This proves that a fresh Mail Server VM can resolve and install the packages using only the Repo VM.

HTTP tests

The verifier will test:

Local HTTP access
Repo VM hostname access
Repo VM IP access
Repository metadata
Rocky signing key
Generated client repository file
