Stage 3 verification scope

The Stage 3 verifier will first require a successful Stage 2 verification.

If Stage 2 is not valid, Stage 3 immediately stops:

DECISION: NO-GO

Reason:
Stage 2 prerequisite repository has not passed verification.

It will then validate the following.

Docker RPM repository

The verifier will check:

docker-ce
docker-ce-cli
containerd.io
docker-buildx-plugin
docker-compose-plugin
Complete RPM dependency closure
RPM signatures
Repository metadata

It will use another clean temporary DNF root to prove Docker can be installed using only the Repo VM.

Mailcow source bundle

It will verify:

Source archive exists
Source archive is readable
SHA-256 matches
Pinned Git commit matches the manifest
Pinned release matches the manifest
docker-compose.yml exists
Required Mailcow scripts exist
Container image completeness

The verifier will parse the pinned Mailcow Compose configuration and obtain the complete expected image list.

It will compare that list against the published image manifest:

Compose image list
        versus
Published image list
        versus
Saved image archive

It will fail on:

Missing image
Unexpected image
Wrong tag
Wrong image ID
Manifest mismatch
Duplicate image entry
Unreadable image archive
Image bundle validation

The package will test:

zstd archive integrity
Archive readability
Bundle SHA-256
Manifest SHA-256
Image count
Image tags
Image IDs
Registry digests, when available

For deep verification, it will use an isolated temporary Docker data root and socket, rather than altering the Repo VM’s normal Docker image store.

The isolated test will:

Start temporary Docker daemon
Load the Mailcow bundle
Verify every expected image and tag
Run docker compose config
Confirm every Compose image exists locally
Stop temporary Docker daemon
Remove temporary validation data

No public image pull will be permitted during this test.

Offline-installer simulation

The verifier will test the generated Mail Server installer in validation mode.

It will confirm that the installer:

Uses Repo VM HTTP URLs
Uses the local Docker RPM repository
Uses the local Mailcow source archive
Uses the local image bundle
Verifies SHA-256 checksums
Loads images locally
Uses docker compose --pull never
Does not configure public Docker repositories
Does not call docker pull
Publication checks

It will verify:

/rpms/docker-ce/current
/images/mailcow/current
/manifests/mailcow/current
/manifests/mailcow/LATEST

It will also confirm that every current link resolves to a valid immutable release directory.

