Example:

Failure ID:
R2-GIT-003

Problem:
git-core-doc version 2.52.0-1.el9 is absent.

Impact:
A clean Mail Server VM cannot install git from the Repo VM.

Required correction:
Rebuild the Git dependency closure from Rocky AppStream and regenerate
the base and Mailcow repository metadata.

Proceed to next stage:
NO
Exit codes

The verifier will return machine-readable exit codes:

0 = GO
1 = NO-GO because verification failed
2 = Verifier itself could not execute
3 = GO with non-blocking warnings

This means the build wrapper can automatically stop the process:

sudo bash ./verify-build.sh || exit 1

Stage 3 will never start automatically after a Stage 2 failure.

Final automated process

The completed Repo VM workflow will become:

Stage 1:
Run LinuxInfra v0.7.2
        ↓
LinuxInfra reports SUCCESS
        ↓
Reboot

Stage 2:
sudo bash ./build-and-verify.sh
        ↓
GO     → Stage 3 allowed
NO-GO  → Stop and review remediation.txt

Stage 3:
sudo bash ./build-and-verify.sh
        ↓
GO     → Repo VM ready for Mail Server deployment
NO-GO  → Stop and review remediation.txt

Later, after both individual stages are stable, we can add one final read-only command:

sudo bash ./verify-repo-vm-readiness.sh

Its final output will be only one of these:

REPO VM READINESS: GO
Ready for offline Mailcow deployment.

or:

REPO VM READINESS: NO-GO
Review the listed blocking failures before building mail1.
